/* This is a recursive solution
For recursion we need 2 main thing:
1) Base case or the terminating condition
2) Next state transition/Recurrence Relation i.e
 A way to move to next from current state/input

 In this problem our base case will be when we have
 iterated through the entire length of array i.e
 when currentIndex >= nums.length

 And we can apply common sense to derive recurrence relation.
 So for currentIndex we have only two choices i.e.
 we can either select/include the number at current index in out set
 or we can exclude/pass the number at current index.
 If we choose to include the number in our set when we can do it by [...set,nums[currentIndex]]
 otherwise if we exclude/pass currentIndex num then our set will remain same as it was earlier i.e set
 And in either case we will increment our currentIndex so that next time we 
 check for another number in nums array

 Now let's look into the code 
 */
var subsets = function (nums) {
	//Array finalOutput stores all the power sets
	let finalOutput = [];

	// Helper method is a recursive function that call's itself
	const helper = (currentIndex, set) => {
		// Check for base case as stated above
		if (currentIndex >= nums.length) {
			// push the set of current iteration in finalOutput
			finalOutput.push(set);
			return; //Necessary to end the recursion iteration
		}

		//This is the 1st case where we are including the currentIndex number
		// We increment currentIndex and add currentNumber i.e nums[currentIndex] in our set i.e. [...set, nums[currentIndex]]
		helper(currentIndex + 1, [...set, nums[currentIndex]]);

		// This is the second case where we are excluding the currentIndex number
		// We increment currentIndex and our set remains unchanged
		helper(currentIndex + 1, set);
	};
	//1st call to recursive function
	helper(0, []);

	// return our power set stored in finalOutput
	return finalOutput;
};
```

