This is a problem associated with binary search
Lets take an example
1-2-3-4-5
G-B-B-B-B

Our objective is to find the first bad version. You can assume it is sorted array by substituting Good by zero and Bad by 1
1-2-3-4-5
0-1-1-1-1
We have to find first 1. We start by find value 1. 
```
mid = low + (high-low)/2; // First approach
mid = (low+high)/2 //second approach.
```
We followed first approach as it would prevent integer overflow, i.e, if sum of low and high is more than the capacity of integer it would pick next number which can become negative. You can read more about it [here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_overflow)

We are interested in finding lower bound where value becomes 1, i.e, Bad, so we need to track only **low**. When our function **isBadVersion** returns true. It means we can find lower bound or if the mid is the lower bound. If mid is lower bound, in next iterations, low will be assigned the value of current **mid**.

Iterations:
1. low=1, high=5, mid = 2, badversion = true
2. low =1, high = 2, mid = 1, badversion = false
3. low=2, high=2, it comes out of loop as low == high
```
/* The isBadVersion API is defined in the parent class VersionControl.
      boolean isBadVersion(int version); */

public class Solution extends VersionControl {
    public int firstBadVersion(int n) {
       int low = 1, high = n;
        while(low<high){
            int mid = low + (high-low)/2;
            boolean answer = isBadVersion(mid);
            if(answer==false){
                low = mid+1;
            }
            else{
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return low;

    }
}
```

