Straightforward linear search solution like
```c++
int firstBadVersion(int n) {
    int version = n;
    while (version > 1 && isBadVersion(version - 1)) {
        version -= 1;
    }
    return version;
}
```

turns into an efficient binary search with just a simple twist:

```c++
int firstBadVersion(int n) {
    int version = n;
    for (int step = n; step >= 1; step /= 2) {
        while (version - step >= 1 && isBadVersion(version - step)) {
            version -= step;
        }
    }
    return version;
}
```

No need to maintain `left`, `right` variables and reason about happens to them on corner cases! Varying step sizes is all you need.

